The court had previously heard from Burnell's lawyer that the defendant would like to pursue youth work and pushed for a conviction not to be recorded.

Lawyer James Maher said Burnell would be required to undergo a background check for work and a conviction would make it more difficult for him to pass one.

But Mr Dingwell knocked back the suggestion as the assault 'was a prolonged and serious assault on a defenceless man'.

Burnell was given a 12-month good behaviour order and required to perform 80 hours of community service.

